-asia/the-pakistan-that-exists-in-purnea-district-of-bihar_100137721.html The Pakistan that exists in Purnea district of Bihar]</ref>\n\n==History==\nPrior to 1947 Purnia district was part of the Nepal Province of [[British Raj|British India]]; in August of that year colonial India was [[Partition of India|partitioned]] into two states, the [[Dominion of Pakistan]] and the [[Union of India|Dominion of India]].\n\nAs Purnia lay adjacent to East Pakistan many Muslims left to migrate there, and the inhabitants of the village renamed it Pakistan after the Muslims who had left. Prior to the [[States Reorganisation Act]] of 1956, the district of Purnia bordered East Pakistan;  afterwards [[Islampur subdivision]] was awarded to [[West Bengal]].<ref name=\"BTimes\"/> Before leaving the Muslims had handed over their property to Hindus of the neighbouring areas.<ref name=\"BTimes2\"/>\n\n[[India\u2013Pakistan relations|Relations]] between Pakistan and India have historically been turbulent. The events surrounding the partition of 1947 have involved millions of refugees fleeing in either direction to escape violence. In addition, since independence from [[British Raj|Britain]], the two nations have fought several wars. However, according to the villagers they do not want a war between the two nations and wish to spread the \"message of peace and brotherhood\".<ref name=\"Dawn\">[http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2009\\01\\03\\story_3-1-2009_pg1_4 \u2018Pakistan\u2019 in Indian state of Bihar]</ref>\n\nThere has never been any attempt to rename the village, which is official recorded in government documents as 'Pakistan'.<ref name=\"BTimes2\"/>\n\n==Geography==\nPakistan  is a tiny village that lies 30&nbsp;km from [[Purnia]], the district headquarters, and is located in Srinagar Block.<ref name=\"BTimes2\">[http://www.bihartodayonline.com/2009/01/this-pakistan-has-no-muslims.html This 'Pakistan' has no Muslims]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Demography==\nSince partition in 1947 the village no longer has any Muslim inhabitants; the inhabitants of the village are Hindus. The people belong to the [[Santals|Santhal]] tribe, the largest tribal group in India.<ref name=\"BTimes2\"/> The village is quite a poor one and reportedly it lacks basic facilities including roads, schools<ref name=\"Dawn\"/> and hospitals. The literacy rate of the district as a whole is 35.51.<ref>[http://gov.bih.nic.in/Profile/CensusStats-03.htm Literacy]</ref><ref name=\"BTimes2\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://indiatoday.intoday.in/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=26190&issueid=111&sectionid=4 This 'Pakistan' has no Muslims]\n\n{{coord missing|Bihar}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Purnia district]]\n", "name_user": "DrKay", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pakistan,_India"}
